annotations: More like eye for eye

The expression “an eye for an eye” comes from the Bible, specifically Exodus 21:23-25, which refers to retributive justice. Retributive justice is a theory of justice that holds that a person committing a crime should be given a punishment proportionate to the crime.

In this context, “eye for eye” refers to the singer and her partner continuing to hurt each other, back and forth. When one partner hurts the other, the other retaliates, hurting the first. The cycle continues, as they break each other’s hearts.

annotations:
I wish you knew what I want

In an [interview] (https://www.thefourohfive.com/music/article/the-aces-share-new-single-waiting-for-you-405-premiere-152) The Aces stated,

“When we were writing the track we were really trying to tune into what the beginning of a new romance feels like. That excitement and anxiety and just desperately wanting that person to reach for your hand. The song captures that very moment of being on the verge of spilling of all your emotions to that person”

I thought I made it clear as crystal
 It doesn’t have to be this hard
 But you ain’t good at reading signals
 When they come straight from the heart

The song starts out with lead singer Cristal Ramirez talking about how she thought she was being clear in her intentions with someone. She’s dropped hints, and she’s come out to straight up say what she’s feeling and what she wants but this person is just not getting it. Perhaps she wasn’t communicating what was on her mind as clearly as she believed she was?

description.plain:
“801” is about each of the members growing up in a religious setting in Provo and learning to find themselves in that space. Utah culture and politics are dominated by the LDS church. The number “801” is the area code for the Wasatch Front in Utah. The song is based on a poem Alisa wrote after going to the only gay club in Salt Lake City.

For Cristal, Alisa, and Katie especially as queer women, finding their own space was difficult growing up. Cristal told American Songwriter:

The biggest thing I’d go back and tell myself as that young girl is that all these things just take time. Keep looking forward and find your community and what brings you so much joy. It doesn’t have to be next door to you. It can be online or a few states over. But they’re there. Don’t lose hope. As a 24-year-old, I look back on 17-year-old me and think, ‘That was a brief moment in time.’”

annotations:
Why I always take it there?
 Gonna lose it, don’t you dare
 I can’t take me anywhere, no

This line is styled like a conversation between two people. It creates the impression that there is an inner dialogue inside the singer’s head: one side panicking, the other attempting to convince her to keep from losing it or freaking out.
And if I cut off all my hair

Many people that struggle with mental illness or are otherwise under emotional distress will impulsively cut their hair or shave their heads. However, this could be a specific reference to Britney Spears, who famously shaved her head in 2007. Spears was also struggling with her mental health at the time, but many believe the pressures of fame and the attention on her appearance were the reason she used shaving her head as a coping mechanism, specifically. This song describes the feeling of having to pretend like everything is fine because everyone’s eyes are on you, so perhaps The Aces are relating to what Spears went through.

description.plain:
According to the Aces, “Stuck” is “inspired by the feeling of being stuck in a situation that you know isn’t right but don’t know how to get out of, whether it is a relationship or a roadblock in life.”

Guitarist Katie Henderson says of the track:

I think that was the turning point in finding ourselves as a band. It was especially a great moment for our career because of the reaction we got to it. It felt validating to know we could get a reaction from people.

description.plain:
“Volcanic Love” is the 80s inspired summer-loving album opener of The Aces. Its music video, co-directed by Nico Poalillo and the band’s drummer Alisa Ramirez, seems to follow that theme, referencing many popular 80s and 90s teen movies such as “Heathers” and “Mean Girls.”

Dealing with a romance that, although toxic and frowned upon, continues to burn with passion, the song is a pop rock anthem that stays with you, with its catchy lyrics and lush guitar riffs.

album.name: When My Heart Felt Volcanic

body.plain:
“Volcanic Love” is the 80s inspired summer-loving album opener of The Aces. Its music video, co-directed by Nico Poalillo and the band’s drummer Alisa Ramirez, seems to follow that theme, referencing many popular 80s and 90s teen movies such as “Heathers” and “Mean Girls.”

Dealing with a romance that, although toxic and frowned upon, continues to burn with passion, the song is a pop rock anthem that stays with you, with its catchy lyrics and lush guitar riffs.

annotations:
My love is leaving
 Before the lightning hits the ground
The relationship is passionate and fast-paced, leaving little room for thinking about the future. This line shows how impulsive the relationship is and implies that it is a summer fling.

While I’m looking forward
 My mind is moving backwards now

This lyric implies that while the singer is trying to move forward, her mind (and relationship) are stuck in the past and regressing. This shows that the relationship is extremely passionate but toxic.

You’re burning me up
 Tell me you feel it now
 You’re burning me up
 I know you need it now
 Lo-o-o-ove, volcanic lo-o-ove
 Lo-o-o-ove, volcanic lo-o-ove

Lead singer Cristal Ramirez told NME that this was one of her favorite parts of the album:

I really love the chorus of “Volcanic Love” because I think it’s very emotional. “Tell me you feel it now” is probably one of my favorite lines because it’s that moment of “you feel it too, right? I’m not crazy because I feel so intensely about you.” That just feels very human to me.
